## Day 3: File and Directory Management

## ğŸ—‚ï¸ 1. Copying, Moving, and Renaming Files

| Command     | Description                      | Example                                      |
|-------------|----------------------------------|----------------------------------------------|
| `cp`        | Copy files/directories           | `cp file1.txt file2.txt`                     |
| `cp -r`     | Copy directories recursively     | `cp -r dir1/ dir2/`                          |
| `mv`        | Move or rename files/directories | `mv old.txt new.txt` (rename)<br>`mv file.txt /home/user/Documents/` (move) |

> âœ… **Tip:** Use `-i` with `cp` or `mv` to confirm before overwriting:
> ```bash
> cp -i file1.txt file2.txt
> ```

---

## ğŸ—‘ï¸ 2. Deleting Files and Folders Safely

| Command     | Description                      | Example                   |
|-------------|----------------------------------|---------------------------|
| `rm`        | Remove files                     | `rm file.txt`             |
| `rm -r`     | Remove directories recursively   | `rm -r folder/`           |
| `rm -i`     | Ask confirmation before deleting | `rm -i file.txt`          |
| `trash`     | Move to trash (if available)     | `trash file.txt`          |

> ğŸ›¡ï¸ **Tip:** Use `trash-cli` to avoid permanent deletion by mistake.

---

## ğŸ—ƒï¸ 3. Creating Backups Manually

| Task                    | Command                            |
|-------------------------|------------------------------------|
| Simple file copy        | `cp file.txt file_backup.txt`      |
| Create archive          | `tar -cvf backup.tar folder/`      |
| Archive with compression| `tar -czvf backup.tar.gz folder/`  |
| Extract archive         | `tar -xzvf backup.tar.gz`          |

> ğŸ’¡ **Backup Tip:** Store backups on a different disk or cloud.

---

## ğŸ“ 4. Best Practices for Organizing Files

- âœ… Use folders to separate content types:  
  `~/Documents`, `~/Downloads`, `~/Projects`, etc.
- ğŸ—“ï¸ Add dates to filenames:  
  `report_2025-06-11.txt`
- ğŸ§¹ Regularly remove unused files and backups
- ğŸ” Use `ls` before any `rm` command to review contents

